Documentation:
* https://support.atlassian.com/provisioning-users/docs/connect-to-g-suite/
{quote}
Product access for previously synced users

If you disconnect your organization, we maintain product access for your previously synced users. When you reconnect the organization, we remove product access from any previously synced users that are not part of the new sync.
{quote}
* https://support.atlassian.com/provisioning-users/docs/set-up-g-suite/
{quote}
Automatically sync product details

If a user already exists in an organization but isn’t in the G Suite group you’re syncing, the user keeps their product access in Atlassian after you sync.
{quote}

Regarding expected sync behavior, the documentation doesn't explicitly mention that once a user is synced, _changing the sync scope_ to no longer include previously synced users would cause those users' Atlassian accounts to be deactivated.

Suggested update - some variation of the below text:
{noformat}
If you disconnect your organization, we maintain product access for your previously synced users. When you reconnect the organization, we remove product access from any previously synced users that are not part of the new sync.

If the sync scope is changed - i.e. sync groups are added or removed, then users who were previously synced will need to be a member of the current sync group(s) in order to retain product access.  The users' Atlassian accounts may be deactivated if the account was previously synced, but isn't part of the current sync scope.
{noformat}

Also....
{noformat}
If a user already exists under the list of "Managed accounts" within the organization admin UI but isn’t synced(initial sync for the user has not happened) and the user isn't in the G Suite group you’re syncing, the user keeps their product access in Atlassian after you sync.  

When a user is synced, product access be removed if a user is no longer a member of any current sync groups.
{noformat}

When SAML is enforced in one authentication policy, you cannot delete the configuration, but instead of informing that this is the reason, the error thrown is generic:
{quote}*Something went wrong, try again later.*
{quote}
But verifying with the developer tools, the true reason is thrown as the response for the HTTP request:
{code:java}
{"code":"SAML_IN_USE","message":"SAML is used by auth policies"}{code}
h1. Ask

To handle the response from the API to throw the correct error message on the UI

Users created over SCIM with product access are not automatically added to the local Product Default Access Group. It's very counter intuitive to be able to setup automation but still require / need to manually set default groups that are required

Example:
 # SCIM-Jira-Users group is synched;
 # SCIM-Jira-Users group has Jira Product Access;
 # Users from SCIM-Jira-Users are not automatically added to the product's local default access group (e.g: jira-software-users).
